<p><strong>1. What is Tomas Björk's arbitrage theory?</strong></p>
<p>Tomas Björk's arbitrage theory, outlined in his seminal 1998 book "Arbitrage Theory in Continuous Time," provides a rigorous mathematical framework for pricing financial derivatives and managing risk under uncertainty. The theory is based on the principles of no-arbitrage and the existence of a unique risk-neutral measure, which is used to discount future cash flows.</p>
<p><strong>2. What are the main applications of arbitrage theory?</strong></p>
<p>Arbitrage theory has numerous applications in mathematical finance, including:</p>
<ul>
<li>Pricing options, forwards, and futures contracts</li>
<li>Hedging investment portfolios</li>
<li>Modeling credit risk and interest rate derivatives</li>
<li>Managing risk in complex financial markets</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>3. Where can I find solutions to Tomas Björk's arbitrage theory problems?</strong></p>
<p>The official website for the book "Arbitrage Theory in Continuous Time" provides a comprehensive set of solutions to the exercises and problems in the text. These solutions are available in PDF format and are essential for understanding the theory in depth.</p>
